summary: Amazing #289 had so many epic moments, like  Peter refusing to die out of spite (this is not about him being suicidal or sth...
body:
Amazing #289 had so many epic moments, like  Peter refusing to die out of spite (this is not about him being suicidal or sth like that, he himself said he had plenty of things to live for - if the desire to break your face takes priority over all of that, you’re screwed), the whole fight with the Hobgoblin II (dregs of the dregs, really - the good parts were Peter threatening him), his speech to Flash, the fact that I’m 95% sure Flash only lived bc his hero gave him mouth to mouth, Kinpin’s prank (I hate the Kinpin, but I hate the Foreigner more - I just don’t like the “untouchable” villains, they frustrate me so much), Peter’s decision to stop waffling and stick to the spider business, etc.

However… like, I get they were still married and stuff, and human feelings are complex and guilt might have been playing the greater part and  all that, but at that point in their marriage… would Betty really go out of her mind over Ned’s death?

Also, while it’s not really unlike him, Peter assuming Ned died because of him was reaally reaching, especially since in SvW he only talked about feeling guilty for not being there to protect him, never talked about the men finding out he was Spider-Man. 

All in all, it feels like they were trying to really drive the drama home, all of it, the good and the bad.

But all the other things gave me so much satisfaction that my brain’s not even making much of an effort to pay attention to what bothers it.

Also, although it feels a bit like a cop out and maybe even a waste, to get rid of the og Hobgoblin before we even found out who he is was such a power move:

 THE EPISODE YOU WERE WAITING FOR!! NO TRICKS!!! THE HOBGOBLIN REVEALED!! he ded
